ie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"2 January 1012–8 August 1088":"2 January 1012–8 August 1088","1012–1088":"1012–1088","1014–Female":"1014–Deceased","1041–1102":"1041–1102","0989–1060":"0989–1060","0989–Female":"0989–Deceased","2 January 1012":"2 January 1012","1102":"1102","1014":"1014","1012":"1012","1088":"1088","1041":"1041","0989":"0989","1060":"1060","8 August 1088":"8 August 1088","Normandel, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Normandel, Orne, Lower Normandy, France","Lot-et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France":"Lot-et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France","Bakewell, Derbyshire, England":"Bakewell, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Caen, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lutre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Old French <i>loutre</i> ‘otter’, either used as a nickname, or alternatively as a metonymic occupational name to denote an otter hunter.","variant of   Luther   2.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Luttrell","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): from a diminutive of Old French <i>loutre</i> ‘otter’ (from Latin <i>lutra</i>), applied as a nickname for someone thought to resemble an otter, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who hunted otters (for their pelts). Compare   Luter   and   Litteral  ."]},{"name":"Lutter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Gerhardt, Gerd, Helmut, Horst, Klaus.","English: variant of   Luter  .","German: habitational name from any of several places so called, for example near Hanover."]},{"name":"Luther","meanings":["German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>liud</i> ‘people, tribe’ or <i>hlūd</i> ‘clamoring, famous’, + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’.","English: metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>luter</i>, <i>leuter</i> ‘lute player’ (Old French <i>leuteor</i>, <i>luthier</i>). Compare   Luter  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Lutar</b> or <b>Luthar</b>: from a personal name of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Symon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Symon de Lutre was born on 2 January 1012, in Lot-et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France, his father, Hugh de Lutre III, was 23 and his mother, Mrs. Hugh de Lutre III, was 23. He married Judith Marie Lawes in 1041, in France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 8 August 1088, in Bakewell, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom,